PAGE COMPONENT PATTERNS
Hero Section
Purpose: First impression, main value proposition, primary conversion point
Key Elements:
Full-screen or near-full height (h-[90vh] min-h-[700px])
Background image with dark gradient overlay (30% opacity)
Small badge/label with icon (service differentiator)
Large headline (H1 - your exact SEO title)
Brief description paragraph (50-100 words)
Two CTA buttons (primary gold + secondary outlined)
Border-left accent on content area
Best Practices:
Keep headline punchy and keyword-rich
Background image should support service context
CTAs should be action-oriented ("Get Free Quote", "Call Dispatch")
Sticky Jump Navigation
Purpose: Quick access to page sections, improves UX on long pages
Key Elements:
Horizontal bar that sticks below main header
5-7 navigation links maximum
Smooth scroll to section IDs
Hover underline animation
Hidden on mobile (shows above md breakpoint)
Best Practices:
Use clear, concise labels (Overview, Services, Process, FAQ)
Each link targets a section ID in the page
Keep labels to 1-2 words when possible
Introduction/Overview Section
Purpose: Establish authority, provide context, introduce main content
Layout Style: Asymmetric two-column
Larger column (7/12): Text content with headline and paragraphs
Smaller column (5/12): Visual element (image, stat callout, or graphic)
Key Elements:
Small label with accent line
H2 section headline
150-250 words of introduction text
Inline CTA or link
Supporting visual with decorative framing
Best Practices:
This is where you establish expertise and service area
Include primary keywords naturally in first paragraph
Mention all service locations (Barrie, Orillia, Simcoe County, etc.)
Tabbed Content Section
Purpose: Organize extensive service details into scannable categories
When to Use:
You have 1,000+ words of service descriptions
Content naturally breaks into 3-5 distinct categories
Want to avoid overwhelming "wall of text" scroll
Structure:
Horizontal tab bar with icon-labeled buttons
Active tab styling (gold background, elevated)
Content area with minimum 600px height
Border-left gold accent on content box
Content Per Tab:
H3 category title
3-4 paragraphs (250-500 words)
Bullet list with checkmark icons (4-6 items)
Image placeholder with descriptive alt text
CTA buttons at bottom (quote + phone)
Best Practices:
Keep tab labels short (2-3 words)
Use icons that clearly represent category
Each tab should feel complete (not cut off mid-thought)
Keywords should be distributed across all tabs
Grid Cards Section
Purpose: Visual showcase of 3-4 main offerings or categories
Structure:
3 or 4 column grid on desktop
Cards with background images and text overlay
Numbered badges (01, 02, 03...)
Hover effects (color shift, image desaturate/scale)
Fixed card height for alignment
Card Elements:
Icon in corner
Small label (category type)
Large title (service name)
Brief description (1-2 sentences)
Background image at low opacity
Best Practices:
Images should be high-contrast and support the service
Keep descriptions brief (50 words max)
Hover effects should be smooth, not jarring
Split-Screen Section
Purpose: Create dramatic contrast for dual concepts
Layout: 50/50 split (or 60/40)
One side: Content (text, headline, CTA)
Other side: Image or contrasting content
Common Uses:
Problem vs Solution
Service Type A vs Service Type B
Content vs Visual showcase
Emergency vs Planned services
Styling Variations:
Dark/Light split (bg-brand-dark + bg-white)
Content/Image split
Emergency/Standard split (red + white)
Best Practices:
Maintain vertical balance between sides
Use high-quality images that fill space
Content side should be scannable (short paragraphs)
Process/Steps Section
Purpose: Explain workflow, procedures, or how service works
Display Format: Grid of cards or vertical timeline
3-6 steps ideal
Each step: Icon + title + description
Numbered or sequential layout
Best Practices:
Keep step descriptions brief (2-3 sentences)
Use action-oriented titles ("Schedule Consultation", not "Consultation")
Visual consistency (all icons same style, all cards same size)
Sticky Sidebar Layout
Purpose: Long-form content with persistent CTAs or info cards
Structure:
Main content column (2/3 width) - scrolls
Sidebar column (1/3 width) - sticks to viewport
Sidebar Card Types:
Primary CTA card (project inquiry, quote form)
Quick contact card (phone number display)
Trust signal card (credentials, certifications)
Best Practices:
2-3 sidebar cards maximum
Top card should be most important action
Sticky positioning: sticky top-32
FAQ Accordion Section
Purpose: Address common questions, build SEO with long-tail keywords
Structure:
Single column layout (not grid)
Narrow max-width for readability (max-w-4xl)
Click to expand/collapse
Chevron icon indicates state
Styling:
Question: Bold, larger text
Answer: Normal weight, smaller text, gray color
Subtle border between items
Hover background highlight
Best Practices:
10-20 questions ideal
Questions should include location keywords when relevant
Answers should be 2-4 sentences (not too long)
Include FAQ schema markup
Emergency/Urgent Section
Purpose: Highlight time-sensitive services or emergency response
Styling:
Background: Red (bg-red-700 or bg-red-600)
Animated icons (pulse, bounce)
Large, bold typography
Prominent phone number or emergency CTA
Best Practices:
Use sparingly (only for truly urgent services)
Make phone number largest element
Include "24/7" or "Emergency" badge
Trust Signals Section
Purpose: Build credibility with credentials and proof points
Common Elements:
Insurance info ($5M liability, WSIB)
Years in business
Certifications/licenses
Equipment owned vs rented
Service guarantees
Display Options:
Badge grid (icons + short text)
Stat counters (large numbers)
Checkmark list
Best Practices:
Keep it concise (not a full section, more like a callout)
Use border accents (border-y-4 border-brand-gold)
4-7 trust items maximum
Final CTA Section
Purpose: Last conversion opportunity before footer
Structure:
Full-width, centered content
Dark background (bg-brand-dark)
Heavy top border (border-t-[16px] border-brand-gold)
Massive headline
Two prominent CTA buttons
Best Practices:
Keep copy brief and punchy
CTAs should be clear next steps
Optional: background image at very low opacity
Contact Form Section
Purpose: Provide dual-path conversion (emergency + planned)
Layout: Split design
Left half: Emergency/urgent contact (dark background)
Right half: Planned/quote request (gold background)
Best Practices:
Make phone number huge and tappable
Provide both immediate and scheduled options
Keep forms short (or link to full form page)
